The paper discusses a method for learning the Universal Value Function Approximator (UVFA) in large MDPs with sparse rewards, which is a common problem in reinforcement learning. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category. The paper also proposes a hierarchical approach to modeling the environment, which involves a high-level dynamic landmark-based map and a low-level value network. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Robotics (cs.RO) categories. The paper also mentions the use of farthest point sampling, which is a technique commonly used in computer vision and image processing, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the proposed method on a number of challenging tasks, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category.
